OBJECTIVE:
The priority message has been partially decoded into 'repair_sequence.txt'.
However, the instructions are scrambled and contain duplicates from
transmission errors. You must process the data to extract the final code.

━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━

TASK: Extract the Repair Authorization Code
───────────────────────────────────────────
The file 'repair_sequence.txt' contains numbered instruction lines:

    STEP:INSTRUCTION:CODE_FRAGMENT

To reconstruct the authorization code:
1. Sort the lines by STEP number (first field)
2. Remove duplicate lines
3. Extract just the CODE_FRAGMENT field (3rd field)
4. The fragments spell out the authorization code

The final code is ALL the code fragments concatenated together
(just the letters/numbers, in order, with hyphens between each).

When you've assembled the code, run:
    ./verify <code>

━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━

USEFUL COMMANDS:
    sort -t':' -k1 -n file     Sort by 1st field numerically
    uniq                        Remove duplicates
    cut -d':' -f3              Extract 3rd field
    tr -d '\n'                 Remove newlines (join lines)

FULL PIPELINE:
    sort -t':' -k1 -n file | uniq | cut -d':' -f3

HINT: After extracting code fragments, join them with hyphens.
      If fragments are: A B C D E
      Code format is: A-B-C-D-E

